poetae tradiderunt] an allusion to Orestes and Alcmaeon with whom the Roman poets Ennius and Accius had made the Romans familiar. Orestes, driven to fury on account of the murder of his father Agamemnon by his mother Clytaemnestra and her lover, Aegisthus, killed his mother, and was haunted by the Furies. Alcmaeon murdered his mother Eriphyle for having betrayed his father Amphiaraus to a death before the walls of Thebes, for the sake of a golden necklace.
